TY  - JOUR
T1  - Advance‐Purchase Discounts and Price Discrimination in Competitive Markets
AU  - Dana, Jr., James D.
Y1  - 1998/04/01
PY  - 1998
DA  - 1998/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/250014
DO  - 10.1086/250014
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 395
EP  - 422
VL  - 106
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - When both individual and aggregate consumer demand is uncertain and firms set prices before demand is known, price?taking firms may offer advance?purchase discounts. Consumers with relatively more certain demands and with relatively lower valuations have an incentive to buy in advance the presence of other consumers with higher valuations and more uncertain aggregate demand increases the price they expect to pay in the spot market. Advance?purchase sales are made to low?valuation customers, as predicted by traditional models of second?degree price discrimination, without assuming that firms have market power.
AB  - When both individual and aggregate consumer demand is uncertain and firms set prices before demand is known, price?taking firms may offer advance?purchase discounts. Consumers with relatively more certain demands and with relatively lower valuations have an incentive to buy in advance the presence of other consumers with higher valuations and more uncertain aggregate demand increases the price they expect to pay in the spot market. Advance?purchase sales are made to low?valuation customers, as predicted by traditional models of second?degree price discrimination, without assuming that firms have market power.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/250014
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/250014
Y2  - 2024/03/23
